definition: to take out/to put out/to provide/to put forward (a proposal)/to come up with (evidence)
to hold/to seize/to catch/to apprehend/to take/(used in the same way as 把[ba3]: to mark the following noun as a direct object)

to go out/to come out/to occur/to produce/to go beyond/to rise/to put forth/to happen/(used after a verb to indicate an outward direction or a positive result)/classifier for dramas, plays, operas etc
not presentable/not fit to be seen in company

sentences.english: Everyone has to try to contribute $10 from money that we have earned ourselves.
sentences.chinese: 每個人都必須努力從自己掙到的錢裏拿出十美元捐獻。

sentences.english: Naturally, the process of coming up with this list wasn't always easy.
sentences.chinese: 當然，拿出這份書名目錄的過程中並非總是很容易的。

sentences.english: She unwrapped the parcel, and took out the mirror it con-tained.
sentences.chinese: 她打開包袱，從裏面拿出鏡子。

sentences.english: A man ran up to President Garfield, pulled out a gun, and fired twice.
sentences.chinese: 一名男子奔向加菲爾德總統，拿出一支槍射擊了兩次。

sentences.english: He took a basketball from under the desk.
sentences.chinese: 他從書桌下拿出一個藍球。

sentences.english: We had to bring out the powerful Cheerio box to get her take the first step.
sentences.chinese: 我們就只有拿出燕麥圈，派託佳佳邁上第一步。

sentences.english: He fished a coin out of a drawer and began scratching off the latex coating.
sentences.chinese: 他從抽屜裏拿出一個硬幣，開始刮開橡膠塗層。

sentences.english: Without further ado, he took out his pen and lent it to me.
sentences.chinese: 他二話沒說，拿出筆來，把它借給了我。

sentences.english: He pulled out a one-gallon, wide-mouth jar and set it on the table in front of him.
sentences.chinese: 他拿出一個一加侖的廣口瓶放在他面前的桌上。

sentences.english: Every Saturday since then, I have taken one marble out and thrown it away.
sentences.chinese: 從那時起，每到星期六，我都拿出一個彈珠扔掉。

sentences.english: I took out my wallet and nervously fumbled for the pictures of my family.
sentences.chinese: 我拿出了皮夾，慌手慌腳地翻出了我的全家福照片。

sentences.english: With that, he held up the leaves and the goblet to show the king.
sentences.chinese: 說完了之後，他拿出葉子和酒杯呈給國王看。

sentences.english: Take out your true skill, to the ground that you use violence.
sentences.chinese: 拿出你的真本事，給你用武之地。

sentences.english: I was glad I had not pulled out the insecticide to begin with
sentences.chinese: 我很高興一開始我沒有拿出殺蟲劑來殺蟲。

definition: to fish out/to take out (from a pocket, bag etc)
to suddenly reveal/to flash (one's ID, a banknote etc)
preparation/to prepare/to intend/to be about to/reserve (fund)
in hand/(a situation is) in sb's hands
to use/to employ/to have to/to eat or drink/expense or outlay/usefulness/hence/therefore
to hold/to contain/to grasp/to take hold of/handle/particle marking the following noun as a direct object/classifier for objects with handle/classifier for small objects: handful
